<br>
Unfortunately we (the bleeding hearts) can't bring up any issue involving money and the government without someone trying to pin the blame on welfare. I simply cannot believe people think that $415 of which less than $50 is probably abused is such a drain on the economy. They glance right over the $1388 per person that goes to corporations and stare at the $415. That $415 includes school programs and help for the handicapped, the $1388 includes helping McDonald's promote McNuggets overseas, but does not include the tax credits Exxon gets for cleaning up their mess in Prince William Sound. <br>
<br>
Yes Starborn there are plenty of welfare abusers but I believe they are in the minority. The idea of terrible welfare abusers got its biggest boost from Ronald Reagan. You see while he was trying to get his budgets favoring trickle down economics and high military expenditures through Congress he kept trying to divert funds from the public programs to pay for them. The best way to do that was to first villify them. So he told the people the story of the welfare queen. The story says there was a woman in Chicago who used eighty different names, thirty addresses, one dozen social security cards and four fictional dead husbands to bilk the government of $150,000. Unfortunately this woman didn't exist. The closest thing they could point to that was it was woman who got $8,000 using two false names. Reagan's people said the story was to prove a point. Yes, it does. Welfare can be corrupted. However, taking money form the civil servants or the EPA or whatever department you think isn't accomplishing there job isn't going to make things better. You want to see overworked and underpaid, follow around one of those people who is a case worker. So although welfare can be corrupted the stories of it are overblown with few substantial case-in-points. I can name one thousand people who have benefitted from welfare at sometime. I can similarly name as many corporations that have bilked the government of MILLIONS of dollars for every person you can name who has bilked the welfare system for THOUSANDS of dollars. <br>
<br>
The idea that consumer responsibility is vital is good, but almost entirely novel. First of all we live in a world economy. Who's to say that if we quit buying glow-in-the dark clocks that the people from Timbuktu are going to give a crap about our countries wetlands? This happens in the third world all the time. Companies can run roughshod over the workers and government and pull out when they have made their money leaving dead land and unemployed impoverished. Then another company can move in offer these people the hope of employment and they will bow to the companies requests. Our own dealings with big tobacco here have taught us companies will lie to protect themselves for even the slightest profit margins. I know, as a smoker, that tobacco kills, yet i smoke anyway, why do the tobacco companies feel the need to lie about it? We still smoke the things knowing they will kill us, yet unregulated the tobacco companies would try to tell us they wouldn't. All for a good public image. So how are we as the consumer to even know which is actually the &quot;good&quot; stuff, let alone which stuff is driving our taxes up do to the pollution? You ever seen a company advertise &quot;bottum line prices, because we use bottum line precautions&quot;. I bet you could put &quot;ten babies killed in the production of this product&quot; and if you offered it at half price it would sell out. That is the nature of capitalism but instead of passing the buck down to the bottum level and merely hoping that the good thing occurs we should hold those ultimately responsible, E.G. the baby killers or paint makers, liable for there indiscretions.<br>
